        <p>The Whitman administration asked the state Board of Education yesterday to require teachers to update their skills at least every five years. Leo F. Klagholz, the Commissioner of Education, told the board that New Jersey is the only state that does not require teachers to keep taking classes in order to renew their license.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The Whitman administration asked the state Board of Education yesterday to require teachers to update their skills at least every five years. Leo F. Klagholz, the Commissioner of Education, told the board that New Jersey is the only state that does not require teachers to keep taking classes in order to renew their license.</p>
        <p>The New Jersey Education Association, which represents 97,678 public school teachers, favors the idea of continuing education but will reserve judgment on the proposal until more details are available, said Lynn Maher, a union spokeswoman.</p>
        <p>NEW JERSEY DAILY BRIEFING</p>
